<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="116" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="10.[189,324,265,291]" box="[189,324,265,291]" pageId="10" pageNumber="116">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,324,265,291]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="10" pageNumber="116" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,324,265,291]" pageId="10" pageNumber="116">Etymology</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[189,1399,310,408]" pageId="10" pageNumber="116">
The specific epithet ‘ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gilasian &amp; van Steenis" authorityYear="2020" box="[450,592,311,337]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Eumerus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="116" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brevipilosus">
<emphasis box="[450,592,311,337]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="116">brevipilosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
’ [Latin] is derived from ‘brevis’ (short) and ‘pilosus’ (pilose), in reference to the very sparse and short pile on the head, thorax and abdomen rarely seen in the genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Meigen" authorityYear="1822" box="[189,293,382,407]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Eumerus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="116" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[189,293,382,407]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="116">Eumerus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
